## Current Workarounds

1. **Nothing.** Genuinely no tool, no calendar, no notebook, no Notion, no group asker dependency that he initiates himself. The closest thing to a workaround is "friends sometimes mention things."
2. **Reactive recovery.** When he finds out late, he attempts to submit late or accepts the loss. There is no preventive workaround at all.
3. **Resignation.** "I do not keep track of why I lose points."

This is the *absence* of workarounds — the most extreme version of the failure mode our problem statement describes.

---

## Key Observations

- He spoke about his own grade penalties with no visible emotion. Not embarrassed, not angry. Flat.
- Took no notes during the interview, did not look at his phone, did not seem distracted — he was paying attention. This is not a careless person. He is a *defeated* one.
- When I asked the "is it your fault" question I was bracing for him to push back. He agreed immediately without negotiation.

---

## Preliminary Insights

- The "passive sufferer" segment is real and may be larger than the active-tinkerer segment (VG-style). It is the group that has *never* engaged with any solution.
- They are the hardest segment to reach with any tool because they will not seek a tool out. They will only adopt one if it is introduced to them by another person — the asker, the bridge — inside their existing social graph.
- They have already internalized structural failure as personal failure. Any solution we eventually build needs to *repair* that framing, not reinforce it. A tool that says "you missed three deadlines this week" lands on top of existing self-blame and may make adoption *worse*.
- The cost on this segment is opaque even to the sufferer. SH cannot tell me how many of his lost points came from platform misses versus other causes. The pain is real but un-quantified, which makes it hard for him to motivate change on his own.

